tion, and the representation of issues affecting trans people. Examining films that chronicle the local (in portraying national and sub-national identities) while also addressing foreign audiences, the book draws on a wide sample of individual responses through post-screening questionnaires and focus groups, as well as drawing on the work of professional film critics and on-line commentators.Key FeaturesThe first internationally comparative and crosscutting study of LGBTQ film, with audience research at its coreExamines LGBTQ festivals in France and SpainLooks at the cross-border impact of the auteur and big-name directorsExtensively covers independent and documentary film production as well as commercially-pitched feature films  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aHomosexuality and motion pictureszFrance. 0aHomosexuality and motion pictureszSpain. 0aHomosexuality in motion pictures. 0aMotion picture audienceszFrance. 0aMotion picture audienceszSpain. 0aSexual minority communityzFrance. 0aSexual minority communityzSpain. 4aFilm, Media & Cultural Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / Direction & Production.2bisacsh1 aWaldron, Darren, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311078044440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780748699209zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748699209423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748699209/original  a978-3-11-078044-4  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPD